function validMountainArray(arr) {
    let n = arr.length, i = 0, j = n - 1;
    while (i + 1 < n && arr[i] < arr[i + 1]) i++;
    while (j > 0 && arr[j - 1] > arr[j]) j--;
    return i > 0 && i === j && j < n - 1;
}
```

    The algorithm starts with two pointers `i` and `j`. Pointer `i` is initialized to 0, and pointer `j` is initialized to the last index. We iterate through the array with pointer `i` while elements are in increasing order. Then, we iterate through the array with pointer `j` while elements are in decreasing order.

Finally, we check if the pointers have moved from their initial positions (i.e., `i > 0` and `j < n - 1`). We also check if both pointers have stopped at the same index (i.e., `i == j`). If these conditions are met, it means that there is a valid mountain array, and we return `true`. Otherwise, we return `false`.

